<head><meta charset="utf-8"><meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0"><title>DIY HVAC permits</title></head>
<body style="margin:0;padding:0;background-color:#ffffff;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;color:#27272a;">
  <div style="max-width:600px;margin:0 auto;padding:32px 20px;">
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">Hey,</p>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">Day 4 of the DIY playbook: permits. Most homeowners do not realize HVAC work often requires a building permit, and many beginner guides skip that entirely.</p>
    <h2 style="font-size:17px;color:#18181b;margin:28px 0 10px 0;">Why the permit matters</h2>
    <ul style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 18px 24px;padding:0;">
      <li><strong>Insurance:</strong> unpermitted work can create ugly claim questions later.</li>
      <li><strong>Resale:</strong> unpermitted mechanical work often surfaces during buyer inspection.</li>
      <li><strong>Safety:</strong> the inspector is a second set of eyes on electrical, refrigerant, venting, condensate, and clearances.</li>
    </ul>
    <h2 style="font-size:17px;color:#18181b;margin:28px 0 10px 0;">What to ask your building department</h2>
    <ol style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 18px 24px;padding:0;">
      <li>Can a homeowner pull an owner-builder permit for HVAC work on a primary residence?</li>
      <li>Does the permit cover electrical work, or is a separate electrical permit required?</li>
      <li>What documents do they want: equipment specs, load calculation, site plan, or model numbers?</li>
      <li>What does the inspector check at final inspection?</li>
    </ol>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">A failed first inspection is not a disaster; it is usually a punch list. Starting work with no permit when one was required is the avoidable problem.</p>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Day 10 is the toolkit: what to buy, rent, or skip.</p>
